{"id": "10640", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=10640", "title": "Original Sin 2 Accessories", "text": "Accessories are types of items, which can be equipped alongside armour in \"\". \nTypes of accessories.\nThere are 3 types of accessories which can be worn by characters: necklace, ring and belt. Necklace and rings provide only magic armour, while belt provides only physical armour to its wearer. Like armour accessories can also be imbued with runes. \nList of Accessories found on Rivellon.\nFollowing tables show what manner of accessories can be bought, crafted or found on Rivellon. Note that, besides unique rarity accessories, all of the values shown in the tables are examples. This applies especially to all accessories from Common to Divine rarity, which may have different additional properties, besides differing armour values which scales with level and rarity of equipment."}
{"id": "21616", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=21616", "title": "Original Sin 2 Action Points", "text": "Actions Points are special kind of attribute used by characters in order to act during combat in \"\".\nHow Action Points Work.\nAction Points are attribute which all characters possess and use in order to: move, attack, use skills and items during combat. All player characters start the combat with 4 points by default, unless special conditions are met. Player character can have at most 6 Action Points in one turn. Note that this limit does not apply to enemies as some enemies (bosses in particular) may have 9 Action Points in total. \nEvery action in combat costs Action Points. Base attack by weapon (by clicking unto an enemy) will always cost 2 Action Points. Action Point price for using skills however, is more varied. \nThe price for using skills is always displayed in the upper part of the display window in form of green dots. The number of green dots shows how much Action Points will casting said skill cost. If player does not have enough Action Points to cast said skill the skill will be greyed out and the action points used for said skill will be colored red. \nAction Points Management.\nGaining Action Points.\nCharacters always regain action points at the start of their next turn in combat. Unless characters have &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Talents\"&gt;Glass Cannon&lt;/a&gt; talent, or are under effects of spells they will always regain 4 Action Points. \nLosing Action Points.\nIn the game there are few ways to lose Action Points gained. The most notorious way of lowering Action Points gained is by using &lt;a href=\"Adrenaline%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;Adrenaline&lt;/a&gt; which is a scoundrel skill that allows character to instantly get 2 Action points in their current turn, but they will loose additional 2 points they would have gained next turn. Thus, instead of 4 Action Points they will receive 2 Action Points next turn. \nLowering Action Point Cost.\nWhile player has limited amount of Action Points which they can use in single turn, it is possible to increase the amount of stuff the player can do by using mechanics which lower the cost of action points for said action. \nSaving Action Points.\nDuring combat it may be wise to end the turn prematurely, especially when character has only 1 Action Point left and are unable to do anything besides movement. This spare Action Point will be carried over to the next turn. Character will therefore start their next turn with 5 Action Points as they gain 4 action points each turn. \nGift Bags.\nWith the release of Definitive Edition Larian added Gift Bags into the game, which add additional content. Some of these Gift Bags need to be manually activated. "}
{"id": "11361", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11361", "title": "Original Sin 2 Aerotheurge", "text": "Aerotheurge is a &lt;a href=\"Attributes%20and%20Abilities%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;combat ability&lt;/a&gt;, that utilises magic known as &lt;a href=\"Aerotheurgy\"&gt;aerotheurgy&lt;/a&gt;, and is essential for learning and casting Aerotheurge skills as well as crucial determining factor of the effectiveness of air based weapons and ammunition in \"\". \nDescription.\nCharacteristics.\nAerotheurge combat ability focuses on dealing air damage, which is resisted by Magic Armour and Air Resistance. Magic Armour prevents negative status effects from affecting characters whereas Air Resistance directly lowers air damage done. The reduction is based on percentage, therefore character with + 10 % air resistance will receive 10 % less air damage. \nAerotheurge combat ability is by default used by 2 preset classes. The &lt;a href=\"Battlemage%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;Battlemage&lt;/a&gt;, which is a warrior preset class, who uses Aerotheurge alongside &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Warfare\"&gt;Warfare&lt;/a&gt; combat ability and the &lt;a href=\"Enchanter%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;Enchanter&lt;/a&gt;, which is a mage preset class, who uses Aerotheurge alongside &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Hydrosophist\"&gt;Hydrosophist&lt;/a&gt; combat ability.\nAerotheurge on its own offers 3 support skills, 1 utility skill, 3 mobility skills and 8 offensive skills. Craftable skills that include Aerotheurge offer 9 support (2 are incarnate infusions) and 2 offensive skills as well as 1 utility skill. Overall Aerotheurge offers 12 support skills, 10 offensive skills, 3 mobility skills and 2 utility skill.\nAerotheurge ability on its own increases air damage from all sources by 5 % per each point invested. Note that in order to learn all Aerotheurge skills, the character needs 5 points in Aerotheurge (either by investment or by bonuses from items).\nDamage of Aerotheurge Skills.\nDamage in \"Divinity: Original Sin II\" is calculated through this exact formula: Damage = (Base Damage) x (1 + Elemental Bonus%) x (1 + Attribute Bonus% + Weapon Skill Bonus% + Misc Bonuses% [if attack]) x (1 + High Ground Bonus% + Crit Bonus%) x ( 1 + Misc Bonus% [if spell])\nDue to skills under Aerotheurge ability being skills they all use the following formula for damage: (Base Damage) x (1 + Elemental Bonus%) x (1 + Attribute Bonus% + Weapon Skill Bonus %) x (1 + High Ground Bonus% + Crit Bonus%) x ( 1 + Misc Bonus %). Additionaly they cannot be cast if caster is affected by &lt;a href=\"Silenced%20%28Status%29\"&gt;Silenced&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Enraged%20%28Status%29\"&gt;Enraged&lt;/a&gt; status effects.\nSimply put for the air damage done by Aerotheurge skills the most crucial elements are: level of the caster, Aerotheurge ability, intelligence attribute, high ground bonus and critical hit bonus. \nAerotheurge skills DO NOT rely on the base damage done by weapons. However weapons affect damage done if they provide boost to any of the above mentioned elements that affect air damage done.\nTherefore in order to boost damage done by Aerotheurge skills it is crucial to increase: Level, Aerotheurge, Intelligence, High Ground Bonus, Critical Hit Bonus. If possible it is wise to lower the air resistance of enemies. Note that bonus to damage provided by Intelligence is smaller than bonus provided by Aerotheurge ability. \nSurfaces and Status Effects.\nAerotheurge ability is focuses on mastering air. Therefore those who use it are most commonly capable of creating electrified surfaces. These can be made from any surface (and cloud) that contains either blood or water, it matters not whether it is blessed or cursed. Electrifying any of these will create electrified surface/cloud.\nAerotheurge skills are also capable of causing a variety of status effects. Below is a table listing all effects caused by Aerotheurge combat ability skills.\nTraders.\nFollowing table shows all NPCs who are guaranteed to sell Aerotheurge skillbooks, with their location and coordinates in the right column, from them. The location shown in the table (and the coordinates) are only for the initial location the NPC is in. Note that some of these may have other skillbooks and goods to sell. &lt;a href=\"Almira\"&gt;Almira&lt;/a&gt; may follow the Godwoken on &lt;a href=\"The%20Lady%20Vengeance\"&gt;Lady Vengeance&lt;/a&gt; if her demands are met. Also note that &lt;a href=\"Lizard%20Dreamer\"&gt;Lizard Dreamer&lt;/a&gt; requires a persuasion check to be passed in order to speak with him, otherwise he (and the whole encampment) will turn hostile. \nAerotheurge Skills.\nAbility Based.\nFollowing tables and sub-sections show Aerotheurge skills that can be learnt by character if they have enough point in Aerotheurge ability. All of these skills can be crafted by combining corresponding scroll with &lt;a href=\"Blank%20Air%20Skillbook\"&gt;blank air skillbook&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Blank%20Air%20Skillbook\"&gt;high tier blank air skillbook&lt;/a&gt;. Note that not all skills have craftable scrolls. In base game (without cheats) skills from 9 level onward (Adept, Expert and Master tiers) can be gained only after escaping &lt;a href=\"Reaper%27s%20Eye\"&gt;Reaper's Eye&lt;/a&gt; island. \nEach skill belongs to a tier that is determined through characters level that determines whether it can be found and purchased and requires certain level in \"Aerotheurge ability\" in order to memorise the skill. Higher Tier skills may require more memory in order to use them in combat, this especially applies to skills that require &lt;a href=\"Source\"&gt;Source&lt;/a&gt; in order to cast them. \nCraftable.\nFollowing skillbooks are classified as craftable for they can be obtained only by crafting them. They cannot be bought from any trader in the game. However it is possible to get them as quest reward or find them as random loot.\nBase skillbooks are obtained whenever non-source Aerotheurge skillbook is combined with another non-source skillbook. Resulting skillbook will be a mix of both skillbooks and will require investment in both combat abilities under which the skillbooks belong. Example: In order to learn and cast Healing Tears, character needs 1 point in both Aerotheurge and Polymorph combat abilities.\nSource skillbooks are obtained whenever non-source Aerotheurge skillbook is combined with source skillbook and vice versa. One way or another there has to be source skillbook involved in crafting otherwise the resulting book will be non-source skillbook. Like base craftable skillbooks these also cannot be bought from traders in game.\nOther Skills.\nOutside of player accesible and craftable skills, there are skills exclusive to NPCs that are also clasiffied as Aerotheurge. Some of these are also accessible in Game Master Mode. Following table also includes skills exclusive to Gift Bag features such as Pet Power which allows player character to cast Infusions unto any summoned creature. These infusions sometimes grant unique skills unseen in the base game.\nItems.\nOutside of skills, the Aerotheurge combat ability affects also all manner of items which can deal air damage. Likewise the Aerotheurge ability can be boosted through items that provide bonus to it. Most notably this includes all arrows, grenades, traps, equipment and lastly runes. \nAmmunition.\nFollowing arrows and grenades are magical items that can be used both in and outside of combat to cause air damage and potentially create water or ice surfaces. All of the following arrows and grenades are empowered by Aerotheurge combat ability. Note that in order to use arrows, character must have bow or crossbow equipped.\nFollowing items are exclusive to Gift Bag features, most notably Crafter's Kit, and as such cannot be obtained, made or otherwise seen in the base game unless the feature has been manually activated.\nEquipment.\nAerotheurge combat ability is best paired with weapons that cause air damage (most commonly staves and wands) and equipment that increases Aerotheurge and Intelligence. \nRunes.\nAll equipment that has rune slots can be inserted with runes that will grant them additional properties. Most important rune for all who rely on Aerotheurge ability is the &lt;a href=\"Thunder%20Rune\"&gt;Thunder Rune&lt;/a&gt;, which increases not only air damage when inserted into weapon but also &lt;a href=\"Dodging\"&gt;Dodging&lt;/a&gt; when inserted into necklace and ring. Lastly the Frost Rune grants Air Resistance when inserted into armour. If the base Thunder Rune of any size is put into \"rune frame\" it will gain additional effects.\n&lt;a href=\"Thunder%20Rune\"&gt;Mystical Thunder Rune&lt;/a&gt; of any size provides 1 point bonus to either &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Scoundrel\"&gt;Scoundrel&lt;/a&gt; (if inserted into armour), &lt;a href=\"Dual%20Wielding\"&gt;Dual Wielding&lt;/a&gt; (if inserted into weapon) and Aerotheurge (if inserted into any necklace or ring) alongside its base effect.\n&lt;a href=\"Thunder%20Rune\"&gt;Thunder Rune of Power&lt;/a&gt; of any size will always provide bonus to &lt;a href=\"Finesse\"&gt;Finesse&lt;/a&gt; (depending on its size) whenever inserted into any equipment."}
